observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our prior years’ audit recommendations that the LCE requires the BAC Chairman to:

Through the assigned focal person/s, ensure the timely submission of POs or contracts entered into by the City Government to the Audit Team within five working days from perfection pursuant to COA Circular 2009-001 dated February 12, 2009 and for monitoring purposes prepare a monthly report on the submitted POs/ contracts;




Consider the use of Document Routing Slip to properly monitor the process flow of procurement of goods and infrastructure projects.

We recommended that the LCE: 

Require the persons responsible to submit the required documentation and for the City Accountant to comply with the provisions of Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 before payment of transactions;




Enjoin the OIC-City Engineer to strictly comply with the provisions of DPWH DO No. 197 s 2016 in the preparation of the ABC to ensure that the basis and ceiling of bid prices are acceptable/reasonable and advantageous to the government;




Instruct the prospective bidders to adhere with the requirements of the aforementioned DPWH DO by not providing OCM mark-up on items specified therein and include the total markup of direct costs of work items in the computation of 5% VAT component.

We recommended that the LCE and the CSWMB of the City: 

Update their ten-year CSWMP and finalize the WACS to include an intensified information and awareness campaign on ecological solid waste management, particularly at the household and business level in coordination with the Barangay Officials in accordance with their CSWMP;

Assist the Punong Barangays and their respective Barangay Solid Waste Committees in finding a suitable location for their permanent Barangay or Cluster of Barangays MRFs or if possible, provide the required funding in the establishment of the said MRFs;

Provide a specific plan to improve and rehabilitate the City MRFs such as provision of funds for acquisition of infrastructure and technical supports relative to the operation of the MRFs, to ensure that these are functioning as to their intended purpose; and

Strictly require employees of the City MRF to strictly observe the provisions of RA 9003 by stopping the practice of burning of solid waste within the vicinity of the MRF.

We recommended that the LCE:

Enjoin the OIC-Supply Officer and the GSO to prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report for Unserviceable Property for the 289 identified unserviceable items and provide the same to the City Accountant for proper recording in the books and the Audit Team for further verification. Also, require both officers to coordinate with the City Accountant to determine the book value of the remaining 160 unserviceable items without verified carrying cost;

Require the City Accountant to derecognize the costs of these properties once the disposal thereof has been completed and the necessary documents are submitted by the OIC-Supply Officer and the GSO;


Direct the OIC-Supply Officer and the GSO to provide a written communication to the Audit Team in the event that a government property becomes unserviceable and strictly refrain from disposal or destruction of unserviceable items without the presence of the Audit Team or its authorized representative as required under Section 79 of the P.D. No. 1445; and

Instruct the officials and employees concerned on the disposal and destruction of the unserviceable properties to submit a written explanation as to why the unserviceable PPE items were not presented to the Audit Team before its disposition.

We recommended that the LCE:

Consider imposing penalties on non-segregation of waste;




Require the City Solid Waste Management Board (CSWMB) to assist the barangays in properly implementing MRFs pursuant to R.A. No. 9003 or the Ecological Solid Waste Management Act of 2000; and

We recommended that the LCE, through:
City Gender and Development Focal Point System (GFPS), in coordination with the City Budget Officer, CPDO and the City Accountant:
Strictly comply with the requirement to appropriate at least five percent (5%) of the current year total budget for GAD-related PPAs to avoid future instances of under-appropriation in accordance with the provisions of RA No. 9710 or the Magna Carta of Women and its IRR;
Avoid incurring over-expenditures without securing prior approval through an Ordinance Authorizing the Use of Savings and Augmentation as mandated under Section 336 of RA No. 7160 or the LGC, and relevant guidelines under the BOM for LGUs;
City Budget Officer, in coordination with the City Accountant/Personnel-in-charge of RAAO, to strengthen internal controls and monitoring mechanisms over GAD-related expenditures by maintaining a dedicated registry for the GAD Fund, as one of the special accounts under the GF, to ensure proper tracking of its appropriation and utilization.

We recommended that the LCE require the City HRMO:
To review the 201 file of employees and look into the appropriateness and consistencies in the issued NOSA/ NOSI to each employee;
To issue updated NOSA to each employee, as necessary;
To reconcile with the Accounting Unit for any discrepancy in the updated NOSA of each employee versus the actual salary paid to each employee; and
In coordination with the City Accountant, to cause the payment of salary differential of employees who were underpaid of their first tranche of their salary stipulated under EO No. 64 or to cause the refund of concerned employees who were overpaid of their salary for the period September 16 to December 31, 2024 due to discrepancies in the NOSA.

We reiterated our prior years’ audit recommendations that the LCE requires the BAC Chairman to:
Through the assigned focal person/s, ensure the timely submission of POs or contracts entered into by the City Government to the Audit Team within five working days from perfection pursuant to COA Circular 2009-001 dated February 12, 2009 and for monitoring purposes prepare a monthly report on the submitted POs/ contracts;
Consider the use of Document Routing Slip to properly monitor the process flow of procurement of goods and infrastructure projects.

Based from the noted deficiencies, the Audit Team recommended the following:

Accountable Officers should strictly remit/turnover their collections to the City Treasurer or the Liquidating Officer and to deposit the same to its depository bank on a regular basis in accordance with Sections 29, 30 and 32 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs.

The City Treasurer should likewise adopt internal control measures to avoid delayed remittance of collections and institute disciplinary action to the concerned accountable officers under her supervision, if necessary;


Secure fidelity bonds for the employees involve in the collection and disbursement process who were not yet bonded, to comply with the guidelines of Section 305 (f) of RA 7160 and Section 4.2 of Treasury Circular No. 02-2009 dated August 6, 2009;



The Local Chief Executive, through the City Treasurer, should adopt a sound internal control system over the requisition of official receipts, and strictly implement that no accountable officer shall be given another set of accountable forms without remitting the collections from the previous set of AFs No. 51; and



Regularly maintain and update the software used for the collections of tricycle permits and franchising to ensure that all transactions can be processed electronically, making the collection procedure more efficient and effective.

We recommended that Management institute an internal control mechanism that ensures all supporting documents were complete before granting the cash advances, such as:

Cash advances for honoraria and/or salaries must be supported with a payroll or list of payees with their net payments;


Avoid using cash advance for payment of procurement for it may defeat the purpose of RA 9184; 


Local travel cash advances must be supported with duly approved travel order and itinerary of travel to avoid granting excessive cash advances; 


Estimate of expenses must also be attached when a cash advance for a specific purpose is being requested;


Cash advances should be reported and liquidated as soon as the purpose for which it was given has been served;


Stop the practice of transferring cash advances of an accountable officer to another employee. Have the responsible accountable officer liquidated his/her own cash advances granted to him/her;


Refrain from payment of honoraria through reimbursement expense receipts and strictly comply with Section 5.2 of COA Circular 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 on the liquidation of cash advances;


Supporting documents such as the PR, PO and AIR must be reviewed thoroughly to ensure accurate documentation of the transaction; and


Submit all the lacking supporting documents in the liquidation of the cash advance as enumerated in COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012.

Based from the deficiencies noted, the Audit Team recommended the following:

Offices and departments of the City Government are encouraged to adopt a system of monitoring mechanism, by utilizing a routing slip to monitor the progress, processing and documentation of disbursement vouchers and as tool in discovering lapses in the procedure or any lacking supporting documents in the financial transaction;


Cash advances and liquidation papers must be properly labeled when complied so as individual liquidations can be easily identified to its corresponding disbursement vouchers;

Also, transmittal letters must also be placed inside the folder detailing the individual cash advances. A suggested format is provided as follows:


Supporting documents, particularly the gasoline invoices and payroll lists, must be placed together with its corresponding disbursement voucher, or if practically impossible, a detailed summary must be attached.

We recommended that Management:
Require the City Engineer to complete the remaining projects in the AIP/Annual and Supplemental Budget for CY 2020;
Direct both the City Engineer and the City Planning and Development Officer (CPDO) to undertake the effective and efficient implementation of the proposed projects within their targeted completion period.

